moewatch  MoE Diagnostic & Audit Library
Complete Technical Specification  •  Post-Research Edition
pip install moewatch

Author: Abinesh  •  GitHub: Abineshabee
Document Version: v0.1.0 •  June 2026  •  Post-Competitive Research


======================================================================
1. WHAT IS MOEWATCH?
======================================================================

moewatch is a lightweight, pip-installable Python library that attaches
to any existing Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) model in HuggingFace
Transformers and gives you real-time diagnostics, training-time alerts,
and actionable fix suggestions — without replacing your training setup.

Think of it as pytest for MoE training. Just as pytest does not replace
your code — it audits it — moewatch does not replace your trainer. It
sits beside it and tells you when something is wrong before you waste a
GPU-day on a collapsed model.

What moewatch IS:
  - A plug-in diagnostic tool for existing HuggingFace MoE models
  - pip install, one line to attach, immediate output
  - Live routing diagnostics from actual forward pass decisions
  - Honest about scope — single GPU in v0.1, community-extended beyond
  - PyTorch-native, Linux/CUDA-first, Colab-validated

What moewatch is NOT:
  - Another WandB / TensorBoard wrapper
  - A replacement for LibMoE or DeepSpeed
  - A new MoE architecture or trainer
  - An enterprise 100+ GPU monitoring platform
  - An Apple MLX or non-PyTorch tool


======================================================================
2. PROBLEM STATEMENT
======================================================================

2.1 The Core Failure Modes
--------------------------
MoE training is fundamentally fragile in ways that dense model training
is not. Four specific failure modes exist that current tooling does not
surface early enough:

  Expert Collapse
    When Discovered Today: After full training run
    Cost: Days of GPU time wasted

  Low Routing Entropy
    When Discovered Today: Manual log analysis post-run
    Cost: Suboptimal model, rerun needed

  Dead Experts
    When Discovered Today: Inference evaluation only
    Cost: Model capacity permanently wasted

  Unstable Router
    When Discovered Today: Loss curve inspection after the fact
    Cost: Hours of debugging with no clear signal


2.2 The Confirmed Tooling Gap
------------------------------
After thorough competitive research across five distinct tools and
libraries, the following gap has been confirmed as real, unoccupied,
and precisely bounded:

  chuk-lazarus
    Backend: Apple MLX only
    MoE Diagnostics: Yes, deep
    Training-time: Partial
    Linux/CUDA: No
    Verdict: Eliminated — Apple Silicon only

  MLXLMProbe
    Backend: Apple MLX only
    MoE Diagnostics: Yes
    Training-time: No
    Linux/CUDA: No
    Verdict: Eliminated — Apple Silicon only

  model-clinic
    Backend: PyTorch
    MoE Diagnostics: Surface only (static weights)
    Training-time: Advisory/callback
    Linux/CUDA: Yes
    Verdict: Adjacent, not overlapping

  LibMoE
    Backend: Own framework
    MoE Diagnostics: Deep
    Training-time: Yes
    Linux/CUDA: Yes
    Verdict: Different category — full framework adoption required

  MixtureKit
    Backend: Own framework
    MoE Diagnostics: Visualization
    Training-time: No
    Linux/CUDA: Yes
    Verdict: Different category — framework adoption required

  moewatch (this)
    Backend: PyTorch
    MoE Diagnostics: Deep — live forward pass
    Training-time: Yes
    Linux/CUDA: Yes
    Verdict: Unoccupied — build it


2.3 The model-clinic Distinction
----------------------------------
model-clinic (v0.4.2, May 2026) is the closest genuine adjacent tool
and deserves honest acknowledgment. It is pip-installable,
PyTorch-native, and includes moe_router_collapse as a named diagnostic
condition. However, it performs static weight analysis on saved
checkpoints — reading tensor statistics post-hoc — not live routing
diagnostics during a forward pass. The distinction is fundamental:

  model-clinic = blood test on a saved sample.
  moewatch     = live heart monitor during the surgery.

The README for moewatch will explicitly acknowledge model-clinic and
explain this distinction. The design of its ClinicMonitor +
ClinicTrainerCallback API pattern is worth studying as a reference.


======================================================================
3. THE IDEA
======================================================================

The idea emerged from a concrete observation: HuggingFace MoE
researchers — training Mixtral, OLMoE, DeepSeek-MoE — discover expert
collapse after the fact. The tooling ecosystem was designed for dense
models and MoEs inherited it without the diagnostic layer they actually
need.

The analogy that crystallized the design: pytest does not rewrite your
code. It attaches to it and surfaces failures. moewatch is pytest for
MoE routing. Attach it. It tells you what is collapsing and when, with
zero modifications to your model or trainer.

3.1 Design Axioms
------------------
  - Non-invasive first. Zero weight modifications, zero training loop
    changes.
  - Attach-anywhere. If you loaded it from HuggingFace, moewatch should
    work on it.
  - Live diagnostics over post-hoc analysis. The value is catching
    collapse at step 2000, not after the run.
  - Honest scope. Single GPU first. No pretending to solve distributed
    until community validates it.
  - Actionable output. Not just metrics — suggestions the researcher
    can act on immediately.


======================================================================
4. OBJECTIVES
======================================================================

4.1 Primary Objectives
-----------------------
  - Make MoE failure modes visible during training, not after.
  - Provide zero-friction installation: pip install moewatch, then one
    line to attach.
  - Work with models researchers already use: Mixtral, DeepSeek-MoE,
    OLMoE.
  - Give actionable fix suggestions, not just metric dumps.
  - Be honest about scope: single-GPU first, distributed later via
    community.

4.2 Secondary Objectives
-------------------------
  - Build community trust through a transparent, scoped v0.1 release.
  - Establish a clear contribution surface for distributed and
    multi-GPU support.
  - Become the standard diagnostic companion for HuggingFace MoE
    models.
  - Acknowledge model-clinic honestly in README — explain what each
    tool does differently.
  - Integrate with WandB and TensorBoard based on user demand in v0.2+.

4.3 Non-Objectives (Explicitly Out of Scope)
---------------------------------------------
  - Building a new MoE architecture.
  - Replacing any existing training framework.
  - Supporting 100+ GPU clusters in v0.1.
  - Generating automatic model fixes (diagnosis only in v0.1).
  - Supporting non-PyTorch backends in v0.1 (Apple MLX, JAX, etc.).
  - Competing with model-clinic on static weight analysis — they do
    that well.


