======================================================================
6. ARCHITECTURE OVERVIEW
======================================================================

moewatch uses PyTorch forward hooks to intercept router outputs
non-invasively. It never modifies model weights or training logic. The
library is structured in four layers:

  Hook Engine
    Responsibility: Attaches / detaches forward hooks on router modules
    Key Classes: HookManager, RouterHook

  Collector
    Responsibility: Aggregates per-step routing statistics
    asynchronously
    Key Classes: StatCollector, RingBuffer

  Analyzer
    Responsibility: Computes metrics — entropy, utilization, collapse
    score
    Key Classes: EntropyAnalyzer, CollapseDetector

  Reporter
    Responsibility: Formats and outputs reports, warnings, suggestions
    Key Classes: AuditReport, CLIReporter


6.1 Core Design Principles
---------------------------
  - Non-invasive: zero modifications to model parameters or training
    loop.
  - Asynchronous collection: hooks write to a ring buffer; analysis
    runs off the critical path.
  - Sampling-based: configurable step interval to keep overhead under
    2%.
  - Graceful degradation: if architecture is unrecognized, warn and
    no-op rather than crash.
  - Single source of truth: all metrics derive from raw routing logits,
    not post-hoc logs.


6.2 Zero-Overhead Guarantee
-----------------------------
moewatch guarantees <2% training throughput overhead in default
configuration. Achieved via:
  - Sampling every N steps (default N=10)
  - Async CUDA reads
  - CPU-side statistics
  - Fixed-memory ring buffer


======================================================================
7. CORE FEATURES
======================================================================

Feature 1 — Dead Expert Detection
-----------------------------------
  from moewatch import audit

  report = audit(model, dataloader)
  report.dead_experts()

  # Output:
  # [DEAD] Expert 7   utilization: 0.01%
  # [DEAD] Expert 12  utilization: 0.00%
  # [OK]   Expert 3   utilization: 12.4%

  - Threshold: configurable, default 0.1% selection rate.
  - Window: rolling N-step window, not cumulative average.
  - Per-layer reporting: dead experts reported per MoE layer, not
    globally.
  - Cold vs dead: warns early for 'cold' experts that may recover;
    errors for confirmed dead.


Feature 2 — Routing Entropy Analysis
--------------------------------------
  report.routing_entropy()

  # Layer 0  entropy: 2.94  [HEALTHY]
  # Layer 1  entropy: 1.82  [LOW]     WARN
  # Layer 3  entropy: 0.21  [CRITICAL] ERROR

  Routing entropy measures how evenly the router distributes tokens
  across experts. Low entropy means the router is concentrating on a
  few experts even if none are technically dead. This is the metric
  most absent from standard training setups.

  - Metric: Shannon entropy of the expert selection distribution per
    layer.
  - Baselines: compares against theoretical maximum entropy (uniform
    distribution).
  - Trend tracking: plots entropy over training steps to detect gradual
    collapse.
  - Layer-wise: separate entropy scores per MoE layer, not a single
    global score.
  - Alerts: configurable thresholds for warning and critical levels.


Feature 3 — Expert Utilization Histogram
------------------------------------------
  report.utilization()

  # Expert  0  ||||||||||||  12.3%
  # Expert  1  ||||||||||||||  14.1%
  # Expert  7  |  0.01%   WARN COLD
  # Expert 12     0.00%   ERROR DEAD

  - Output: ASCII histogram in terminal; JSON-exportable data for
    pipelines.
  - Normalization: percentages relative to total tokens processed in
    window.
  - Color coding: green (healthy), amber (cold/low), red
    (dead/critical).
  - Comparison mode: side-by-side histograms across training
    checkpoints.


Feature 4 — Training-Time Live Alerts
---------------------------------------
  from moewatch import MoEWatch

  watcher = MoEWatch(model)
  watcher.attach(trainer)   # works with HuggingFace Trainer

  # [Step 1000] OK   All experts active, entropy: 2.81
  # [Step 2000] WARN Expert 11 cold  (util: 0.3%)
  # [Step 3000] ERR  Expert 11 DEAD. Entropy drop 45%.
  # [Step 3000] TIP  Suggestion: raise aux_loss_coef to 0.04

  - Trainer integration: HuggingFace Trainer callbacks (TrainerCallback
    interface).
  - Standalone mode: step-based hooks for custom training loops.
  - Alert levels: INFO (normal), WARN (degrading), ERROR (critical
    collapse).
  - Configurable frequency: default every 100 steps, configurable.
  - Silent mode: structured JSON output for integration with existing
    logging.


======================================================================
8. DIAGNOSTIC API REFERENCE
======================================================================

8.1 audit() — Primary API
---------------------------
  from moewatch import audit

  report = audit(
      model,           # any HuggingFace MoE model
      dataloader,      # optional: sample batches
      steps=50,        # how many batches to sample
  )

  report.summary()          # full human-readable report
  report.dead_experts()     # list of dead/cold experts
  report.routing_entropy()  # per-layer entropy scores
  report.utilization()      # per-expert token %
  report.recommendations()  # fix suggestions (v0.2)
  report.to_json()          # machine-readable export


8.2 MoEWatch — Training-Time Monitor
--------------------------------------
  from moewatch import MoEWatch, WatchConfig

  config = WatchConfig(
      dead_threshold=0.001,   # 0.1% default
      entropy_warn=0.6,       # 60% of max
      entropy_critical=0.4,   # 40% of max
      window_steps=500,       # rolling window
      sample_every=10,        # overhead control
      log_every=100,          # alert frequency
      output='console',       # or 'json'
  )

  watcher = MoEWatch(model, config=config)
  watcher.attach(trainer)
  watcher.detach()            # clean removal when done


8.3 Auto-Detection of Router Layers
-------------------------------------
A key engineering challenge: different MoE architectures structure
their router modules differently. moewatch implements a two-pass
auto-detection strategy:

  - Named module scan: walks model.named_modules() for known patterns
    (MixtralSparseMoeBlock, OlmoeMoE, etc.)
  - Heuristic fallback: identifies modules with 'router', 'gate', or
    'sparse' in class name.
  - Manual override: user can specify
    router_modules=['model.layers.0.block_sparse_moe'] explicitly.
  - Graceful failure: if nothing detected, emits a clear warning and
    returns a no-op watcher rather than crashing.


======================================================================
9. METRICS REFERENCE
======================================================================

Expert Utilization
  Formula: tokens_to_expert_i / total_tokens
  Healthy Range: > 1% per expert
  Alert Threshold: < 0.1% = dead

Routing Entropy
  Formula: H = -sum( p_i * log(p_i) )
  Healthy Range: > 80% of max entropy
  Alert Threshold: < 50% = critical

Load Imbalance Score
  Formula: max_util / mean_util
  Healthy Range: < 3x
  Alert Threshold: > 5x = alert

Entropy Trend
  Formula: delta H over last 500 steps
  Healthy Range: Stable or increasing
  Alert Threshold: Drop > 20% = warn

Cold Expert Duration
  Formula: Steps since last selection
  Healthy Range: < 200 steps cold
  Alert Threshold: > 500 steps = dead

All thresholds are configurable via WatchConfig. Defaults are derived
from empirical observations in the MoE training literature: Switch
Transformer, Mixtral, and DeepSeek-MoE papers.


